<br>
Signiture graphics:  E-mail either myself or Deloit, (preferably Deloit since she is the only one who can upload files to the site) me mainly only if your sending a bunch of files or a larger file and cant zip it up since my normal e-mail IS still recieving e-mail and my DSL connection will allow for a pretty quik reception of large, unzipped files, wheras I dont know about Del's hotmail addy doing the same or not.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>make sure</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> that all sig graphic files are at a resolution of no more than 72 dpi, not only will it take up less space, but people on the boards you use the sig on will thank you for the easier to load pics.<br>
<br>
your sig picture is at a higher resolution?  No problem, computer screens see all pictures at 72 dpi (or on some machines now, ppi) if you have an image all set and beutiful at 150 dpi, and change it to 72 dpi, it will look NO different on the computer screen.  The only time a larger res than 72 dpi is needed is for printed media.  Keep a larger res version in case you plan on enlarging or altering the graphic later on, but the one we recieve cannot be larger thn 72 dpi.<br>
<br>
I would also ask that they be no more than 50k in file size, but we will see about that.  I'm not sure about what is a reasonable size there.<br>
<br>
now, as to size in respect to pixels in height and width. . . . <br>
<br>
it should be no taller really than Deloit's, and that is 180 pixels high, we can strech that to 200pixels high, but try not to.<br>
width is another matter, the boards are only so wide, if your sig is wider, it will force people to scroll to the right to read threads containing overly wide signitures.  so I have measured the boards at roughly 600 pixels wide, keep sig pictures to no more than 500 pixels wide.<br>
<br>
why limit hieght and width?<br>
because we do not want a signiture taking up too much of a screen, it makes reading threads more of a chore, also, the larger the linear size, the larger the file size, too large a file size and people will have dificulties opening the thread up!<br>
<br>
at those guidelines your requirements stand at:<br>
